# CodeDNA v0.5

Every source file in this project must have a CodeDNA module docstring as the very first block.

## Module docstring format

```python
"""filename.py — <what it does, ≤15 words>.

deps:    other_file.py → symbol | none
exports: public_function(arg) -> return_type
used_by: consumer_file.py → consumer_function
tables:  table_name(col1, col2) | none
rules:   <hard constraint agents must never violate>
"""
```

## Rules on every edit

- Re-read `rules:` as your **first** step — never violate these constraints
- Follow `deps:` before modifying function signatures
- Read `Depends:` / `Rules:` in function docstrings before writing logic there
- Apply `Modifies:` cascade changes in the same edit session
- Never rename `exports:` symbols without explicit instruction

## Rules on generate

- Write the module docstring before any imports
- For cross-file functions, add a Google-style docstring with `Depends:` and `Rules:`
- At the dangerous call site, add an inline comment: `# includes X — filter Y below`
- Use semantic variable names: `list_dict_users_from_db = get_users()`

## Function-level annotations (sliding-window safety)

```python
def process(arg: type) -> return_type:
    """Short description.

    Depends: config.MAX_ITEMS — hard cap; read before writing logic.
    Rules:   MUST cap before returning; exceed = compliance bug.
    """
    raw = get_all_items()  # includes inactive items — filter is_active=True below
    ...

TIMEOUT = 30  # @SEE: config.py → DEFAULT_TIMEOUT (keep in sync)
```

## Legacy inline tags (still valid)

For backwards compatibility, these tags remain valid inside function bodies:
- `# @REQUIRES-READ: file → symbol` — read before writing logic
- `# @MODIFIES-ALSO: file → fn()` — update after editing this
- `# @SEE: file → symbol` — read if uncertain

## Planner read protocol

When planning changes across multiple files, read only the module docstring (first 8–12 lines) of each file. Use `rules:` presence to filter for task-relevant files. Build a `deps:` → `exports:` graph. Open only the relevant files in full.
